<body>
<div>
<pb facs="#facs_1" n="1" xml:id="img_0001"/>
<ab facs="#facs_1_r2">
<lb facs="#facs_1_l_1599" n="N001"/>
<add place="in-line">Received </add>
<add place="in-line">
<date when="1921-07-21">July 21st 1921</date>
</add>
<lb facs="#facs_1_l_1588" n="N002"/>
<placeName ref="#place-7002482">Baghdad</placeName>
<date when="1921-06-12">June 12 </date>
<lb facs="#facs_1_l_1611" n="N003"/>
1921
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l3" n="N004"/>
Dearest
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH006">Father</persName>
. There has been no mail this
<lb facs="#facs_1_l_1617" n="N005"/>
week - confound all postmen. It has also been rather
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l6" n="N006"/>
a tiresome week because of the Feast of Bairam, the 3 days
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l7" n="N007"/>
feast at the end of Ramadhan. We contrived to spread it out to 4 days,
<lb facs="#facs_1_l_1648" n="N008"/>
for this reason - the calendar new moon was on Monday, but Monday
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l9" n="N009"/>
evening was cloudy + I'm persuaded no one saw the moon. The
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l10" n="N010"/>
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
Sunnis
<note type="editorial">One of the two main sects of the Islamic religion.</note>
</seg>
however pretended they did + "breakfasted" as it's called.
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l11" n="N011"/>
The
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
Shi'ahs
<note type="editorial">One of the two main sects of the Islamic religion.</note>
</seg>
with a
<foreign xml:lang="de">würdig</foreign>
air declared they weren't satisfied +
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l12" n="N012"/>
did not breakfast. So their feast went on till Friday + since
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l13" n="N013"/>
it was Friday + the Shi'ahs were still feastig, no one did
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l14" n="N014"/>
any work.
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH007">Mr Garbett</persName>
+ I paid a lot of congratulatory calls,
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l15" n="N015"/>
on Tuesday, beginning with
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH068">the Naqib</persName>
at 7 a.m. I said I hoped
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l16" n="N016"/>
we hadn't come too early. "Oh no" he replied "I've been
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l17" n="N017"/>
receiving visitors since dawn." They are rather
<foreign xml:lang="fr">jejune</foreign>
occasions
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l18" n="N018"/>
these 'Id visits ('Id = Feast). You eat sweetmeats +
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l19" n="N019"/>
drink coffee + sherbet, with an inward hope that the latter
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l20" n="N020"/>
mayn't be full of typhus germs. And you carry on a colourless
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l21" n="N021"/>
conversation - at least I did, for I did not wish to
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l22" n="N022"/>
embark on controversial politics. The Naqib sent you many
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l23" n="N023"/>
messages, as he always does. I paid more calls by myself
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l24" n="N024"/>
in the afternoon, but next day I confined myself to a
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l25" n="N025"/>
before-breakfast call on
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH029">Haji Naji</persName>
who as a Shi'ah
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l26" n="N026"/>
had just breakfasted. On Thursday I called on some
<lb facs="#facs_1_l_1691" n="N027"/>
Shi'ah ministers + also on the balance of the Naqib family
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l28" n="N028"/>
who all live in a quarter just behind my house. The
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l29" n="N029"/>
eldest son of the Naqib,
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH036">Saiyid Mahmud</persName>, I found holding
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l30" n="N030"/>
his
<foreign xml:lang="fr">levée</foreign>, in a
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
diwan
<note type="editorial">“Diwan” usually means government building or chambers, or historically referred to an official. The context here suggests Bell is referring to some sort of chamber.</note>
</seg>
inside the sacred precincts of
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l31" n="N031"/>
the
<objectName type="Mausoleum" n="MausoleumofAbdul-QadirGilani" ref="#object-EH001">Qadiriyah shrine</objectName>, the burial place of his ancestor
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l32" n="N032"/>
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH037">'Abdul Qadir</persName>, so I joined the company of Sunni
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l33" n="N033"/>
doctors + we talked of - the breeds of Arab horses +
<lb facs="#facs_1_r2l34" n="N034"/>
of how peculiarly beneficent to the horse are the waters
</ab>
<ab facs="#facs_1_r1">
<lb facs="#facs_1_l" n="N001"/>
conviction that no people likes permanently to be
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l3" n="N002"/>
governed by another. Last year when they were
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l4" n="N003"/>
all crying for
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH038">Abdullah</persName>
it wasn't for his
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l5" n="N004"/>
<foreign xml:lang="fr">beaux yeux</foreign>
nor because they were inspired
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l6" n="N005"/>
by Nationalist enthusiasm, but because they
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l7" n="N006"/>
thought the cry was anti-British. I perceived
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l8" n="N007"/>
it at the time + used to say to them that
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l9" n="N008"/>
Abdullah would never dream of coming if he
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l10" n="N009"/>
were not assured of British support - which
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l11" n="N010"/>
was true - but I always felt that it was
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l12" n="N011"/>
a gross want of statecraft on our part to
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l13" n="N012"/>
have let the idea crystallize that Nationalism
<lb facs="#facs_1_l_1463" n="N013"/>
was anti-British. Now we' re trying to foster
<lb facs="#facs_1_l_1492" n="N014"/>
Nationalism but I'm always ready to admit
<lb facs="#facs_1_l_1527" n="N015"/>
that Nationalism which is not at the same
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l20" n="N016"/>
time anti-Foreign is likely to be a plant of
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l21" n="N017"/>
weak growth.
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH001">Faisal</persName>
walking hand in hand with
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l22" n="N018"/>
us will not be so romantic a figure as
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l23" n="N019"/>
Faisal leading
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
a Jihad
<note type="editorial">Arabic word meaning 'strive' or 'struggle'; the meaning of this word depends on context and has different connotations and translations accordingly.</note>
</seg>
might be! He won't
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l24" n="N020"/>
head a Jihad; that's not his line. Can we
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l26" n="N021"/>
get enough of the breath of life into him without it,
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l27" n="N022"/>
to enable him to put real inspiration into the
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l28" n="N023"/>
Arab state - enough to enduce men to enlist
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l30" n="N024"/>
in the army for example? All depends on his
<lb facs="#facs_1_l_1552" n="N025"/>
personality +
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH002">Sir Percy</persName>'s discretion in keeping in the
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l35" n="N026"/>
background. Well at least we're sure of the second item.
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l37" n="N027"/>
Ever your very affectionate daughter Gertrude
</ab>
<pb facs="#facs_2" n="2" xml:id="img_0002"/>
<ab facs="#facs_2_r1">
<lb facs="#facs_2_l" n="N001"/>
of Euphrates!
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l2" n="N002"/>
Things are at last beginning to move. Telegrams
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l3" n="N003"/>
have come from
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH039">King Husain</persName>
saying that
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH001">Faisal </persName>
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l4" n="N004"/>
leaves for the
<placeName ref="#place-1000118">'Iraq</placeName>
this week - a fact of
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l6" n="N005"/>
which we were already aware. We now have to prepare
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l7" n="N006"/>
the way for him. An inspired
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
Reuter
<note type="editorial">Bell may be using this term to refer to published news in general (in reference to the Reuters news organisation), or possibly a rider/horseman, both of which make sense in context.</note>
</seg>
is to be sent
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l8" n="N007"/>
from home tomorrow + next day
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH028">Mr Churchill</persName>
makes
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l9" n="N008"/>
a statement on lines suggested by
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH002">Sir Percy</persName>. After
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l10" n="N009"/>
that Sir Percy will have a heart to heart talk with
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l11" n="N010"/>
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH068">the Naqib</persName>
+ advise him as a friend not to come
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l12" n="N011"/>
forward as a candidate on account of his great age.
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l13" n="N012"/>
The
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH040">
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
Shaikh
<note type="editorial">Honorific title meaning 'Elder', used for leaders of tribes and royal family members.</note>
</seg>
of Muhammarah
</persName>, by the bye, has
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l14" n="N013"/>
already withdrawn.
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l15" n="N014"/>
What everybody wants is to know our wishes + be
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l16" n="N015"/>
guided by them + as soon, as they get any kind of lead
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l17" n="N016"/>
they will all, I think, come into line. Meantime, in
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l18" n="N017"/>
my rôle as the
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
Nabi 'Isa
<note type="editorial">Name used in Qur'an to refer to Jesus Christ.</note>
</seg>
I receive many agitated
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l19" n="N018"/>
visits from my young
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
Sharifian
<note type="editorial">Term referring to things related to the Sharif (a title used to describe those - usually royal - claiming descent from the prophet Muhammad), in this people loyal to Faisal, the Sharif, and his rule.</note>
</seg>
friends asking for
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l20" n="N019"/>
reassurances + for guidance, which I give to the
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l21" n="N020"/>
best of my ability + according to Sir Percy's directions.
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l22" n="N021"/>
He is a master hand at the game of politics; it's
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l23" n="N022"/>
an education to watch him playing it.
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l24" n="N023"/>
I told you about
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH041">Marie</persName>'s falling off a pony-
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l25" n="N024"/>
she didn't seem to get any less lame so finally
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l26" n="N025"/>
we had her X rayed + found that she had
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l27" n="N026"/>
cracked a bone. It's not serious + will
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l28" n="N027"/>
probably be better in another fortnight, only she
</ab>
<ab facs="#facs_2_r2">
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l1" n="N001"/>
is told to walk as little as possible - she need not
<lb facs="#facs_2_l_1110" n="N002"/>
go completely to bed, to my relief. It's very boring
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l4" n="N003"/>
for her, poor thing
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l5" n="N004"/>
I've just had this Sunday morning a long visit
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l6" n="N005"/>
from 2 big shaikhs,
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH042">Fahad Beg</persName>
of the
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
'Anizah
<note type="editorial">Tribe originating from Arab peninsula, placed within the Rabi'a branch of Adnanite tribes.</note>
</seg>
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l7" n="N006"/>
(the giver of my dogs) +
<persName ref="metadata/people.xml#person-EH043">'Ali Sulaiman</persName>, of the
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l8" n="N007"/>
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
Dulaim
<note type="editorial">Large Sunni Arab royal tribe.</note>
</seg>. Both came down from
<placeName ref="#place-1079402">Ramadi</placeName>
to
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l9" n="N008"/>
see Sir Percy + find out his views. They have
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l10" n="N009"/>
hitherto been running a campaign on behalf
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l11" n="N010"/>
of the Naqib, on the ground that they are
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l12" n="N011"/>
perfectly content under our administration +
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l13" n="N012"/>
know the Naqib to be entirely submissive to
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l14" n="N013"/>
Sir Percy's wishes. So they have been told
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l15" n="N014"/>
to stay here for a day or two, when
<choice>
<abbr>H. M. G.</abbr>
<expan>His Majesty's Government</expan>
</choice>
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l16" n="N015"/>
will make pronouncements.
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l17" n="N016"/>
I don't for a moment hesitate about the
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l18" n="N017"/>
lightness of our policy. We can't continue direct
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l19" n="N018"/>
British control though the country would be
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l20" n="N019"/>
better governed under it, but it's rather
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l21" n="N020"/>
a comic position to be telling people
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l22" n="N021"/>
over + over again that whether they like
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l23" n="N022"/>
it or not they must have Arab, not
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l24" n="N023"/>
British govt.
<lb facs="#facs_2_r2l25" n="N024"/>
At the back of my mind there's the firm
</ab>
